Comment: Once again;
Continuing to cover pre-existing conditions, but getting rid of the mandate and premium subsidies will add up to an even sicker and more expensive risk pool than we have today, because the currently healthy will choose to go uninsured. That is, until one day when they "need" insurance. It's simple math, it will cause rates will go up even higher. Unless the uninsured accident or  illness won't wait till the January 1 open enrollment period. In that case their care will likely become either uncompensated care or a partial write-down, which then drives the cost up even more for those that responsibly have insurance.

When will the Republicans learn that you can't have your cake and eat it too.If anybody, regardless of health condition, can get covered, then everybody has to have an obligation to be covered. It's the only way it will work. You also have to have subsidies so premium costs represents some reasonable maximum percentage of income.
